<TITLE> All 7 Birshreshthhos back home at last </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 14 (bdnews24.com)  All the seven Birshreshthhoswar heroes posthumously conferred the highest gallantry award for their role in the freedom struggleare now in Bangladesh on the eve of this year's Victory Day celebrations. The nation has been pining since Dec 16, 1971 for the mortal remains of two of her most valiant sons, Flight Lieutenant Matiur Rahman and Sepoy Hamidur Rahman who spilled their blood in Pakistan and India fighting for Bangladesh in the 1971 War of Independence. Finally, after almost four decades into independence the two were rubbed with the soil of their beloved homeland. The other five Birshreshthhos: Sepoy Mohammad Mostafa Kamal, Captain Mohiuddin Jahangir, Lance Naik Munshi Abdur Rouf, Artificer Ruhul Amin and Noor Mohammad Sheikh received proper burials in their own soil in 1971. The remains of Matiur were brought in from the Mashrur Air Base in Pakistan in June 24, 2006 and buried at the Martyred Intellectuals Memorial graveyard in Mirpur. The remains of Sepoy Hamidur Rahman were brought back from India's Tripura state on June 11 and buried with state honours beside Matiur at the same burial ground Tuesday. bdnews24.com
